  doi = {10.1016/j.jpubeco.2008.01.007},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Using life satisfaction data across countries and within
  countries over time, the authors estimate that the elasticity of marginal
  utility of income is approximately 1.26, implying a logarithmic utility
  function. This means that a 1\% increase in income generates the same utility
  gain regardless of baseline income level. The finding is remarkably robust
  across different methodologies and datasets.

  RELEVANCE: This paper provides the empirical foundation for understanding how
  income affects welfare. The elasticity estimate near 1.0 supports using
  logarithmic utility in policy analysis. However, the paper does not distinguish
  between income and wealth effects, treating all monetary resources equivalently.
  This creates an opening for the research project to investigate whether wealth
  might have a different (steeper) elasticity than income flows.

  POSITION: Represents the happiness economics approach to estimating marginal
  utility, contrasting with consumption-based methods. Foundational for modern
  welfare economics.
